      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument for \"tough on crime\" laws is no longer as strong as it once was, as decades of data show they often fail to lower long-term recidivism while disproportionately harming marginalized communities. Modern criminology now emphasizes that effective public safety requires addressing root causes like poverty, education, and mental health rather than relying solely on harsher penalties. While some states still use these policies, the consensus has shifted toward more holistic approaches that prioritize rehabilitation over simple incarceration.",
